    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>The Java <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/Date.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Date</a> and <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/Calendar.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Calendar</a> classes are considered by many to be poorly designed.  You should take a look at <a href=\"http://www.joda.org/joda-time/\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Joda Time</a>, a library commonly used in lieu of Java's built-in date libraries.</p>\n\n<p>The equivalent of <code>DateTime.Now</code> in Joda Time is:</p>\n\n<pre><code>DateTime dt = new DateTime();\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><strong>Update</strong></p>\n\n<p>As noted in the comments, the latest versions of Joda Time have a <code>DateTime.now()</code> method, so:</p>\n\n<pre><code>DateTime dt = DateTime.now();\n</code></pre>\n"
